ast century's tumultuous early decades, The Power of Position is the first to focus on Beida, China's oldest and best-known national university.Timothy B. Weston portrays the university as a key locus used by intellectuals to increase their influence in society. Weston analyzes the links between intellectuals' political and cultural commitments and their specific manner of living. He also compares Beijing's intellectual culture with that of the rising metropolis of Shanghai. What emerges is a remarkably nuanced and complex picture of life at China's leading university, especially in the decades leading up to the May Fourth Movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHigher education and statezChinaxHistory. 0aPolitical culturezChinaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aacademia.  abeida.  abeijing university.  abeijing.  achina.  achinese anarchism.  achinese culture.  achinese history.  achinese intellectuals.  achinese republic.  achinese students.  acitizenship.  acollege campus.  acollege.  acultural revolution.  ademocracy.  afree speech.  ahigher education.  ahistory.  aintellectual culture.  amay fourth movement.  anational university.  anonfiction.  apeoples republic.  apolitics.  aprotest.  arebellion.  aresistance.  ashanghai.  asocial change.  asocial influence.  asocial standing.  astudent protest.  astudent.  atiananmen square.  auniversity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023767440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092990640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520929906423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520929906/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Pack